                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/4096: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Schurman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-09-23T11:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 23, 1922—11 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received September 23—3:39 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>378. Your 230, September 21, 7 p.m. Yes. Italy refuses, France cannot as funds
                    practically pledged for rehabilitation Banque Industrielle de Chine. England,
                    Japan opposed principle but [if] other interested nations consented they might
                    follow. English suggested to the Chinese Government postponement for one year
                    but no result followed. Matter tacitly dropped.</p>
                <p>I promptly informed Chinese Government of attitude of Department as set forth in
                    the Department’s 193 August 2, 2 p.m. On two subsequent occasions Koo<note
                        n="84" xml:id="d601fn84">Dr. V. K. Wellington Koo. Chinese Minister in Great
                        Britain.</note> informed me other nations were not disposed to postpone
                    indemnity payments and wanted me to ask Department to remove its condition of
                    postponement namely similar action on the part of other interested nations, but
                    I refused, feeling such request should properly reach Department through Chinese
                    official sources.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Schurman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
